  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Scale-Translation Functor.}\n\\begin{equation}\nF:\\mathrm{LabGyro}\\longrightarrow\\mathrm{AstroRot}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Functorial Composition Law.}\n\\begin{equation}\nF(g\\circ f)\n=\nF(g)\\circ F(f).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Natural Equivalence Witness.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\eta:F\\Rightarrow G .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\mathrm{LabGyro}$ be a category of laboratory gyromagnetic systems and $\\mathrm{AstroRot}$ a category of astrophysical rotating systems.\n\nA scale-translation functor assigns:\n\\begin{equation}\nF:\\mathrm{LabGyro}\\to\\mathrm{AstroRot}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nTo preserve dynamical structure, it must preserve composition:\n\\begin{equation}\nF(g\\circ f)=F(g)\\circ F(f).\n\\end{equation}\n\nIf two such translations $F$ and $G$ encode the same cross-scale content, a natural transformation witnesses their equivalence:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\eta:F\\Rightarrow G .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nFractalNodes supply a categorical bridge between laboratory gyromagnetic behavior and astrophysical rotating systems.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
